Interface DateLike

All Known Implementing Classes:
JsDate
public interface DateLike

An opaque interface resembling JavaScript built-in Date objects for manipulating dates and times.

This interface must be implemented in JS Simulation Libraries.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
See Also:
Js.date(), Js.date(Number), Js.date(String), JsDate.JsDate(js.core.JsObject), JsDate.JsDate(Number), JsDate.JsDate(NumberLike), JsDate.JsDate(String), JsDate.JsDate(StringLike), JsDate.JsDate(Object, Object), JsDate.JsDate(Object, Object, Object), JsDate.JsDate(Object, Object, Object, Object), JsDate.JsDate(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object), JsDate.JsDate(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object, Object), JsDate.JsDate(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object, Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.create(), JsGlobal.Date.create(Vars), JsGlobal.Date.create(Number), JsGlobal.Date.create(NumberLike), JsGlobal.Date.create(Object), JsGlobal.Date.create(Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.create(Object, Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.create(Object, Object, Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.create(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.create(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.create(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object, Object, Object), DateLikes

Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

Method Detail

getTime

java.lang.Number getTime()

Returns the internal, millisecond representation of the current date instance.

It converts the current date instance to a single integer. This is useful when you want to compare two date instances or to determine the time elapsed between two dates. Note that the millisecond representation of a date is independent of the time zone, so there is no getUTCTime() method in addition to this one. Don't confuse this method with the getDay() and getDate() methods, which return the day of the week and the day of the month, respectively

JsGlobal.Date.parse(Object) and JsGlobal.Date.UTC(Object, Object) allow you to convert a date and time specification to a millisecond representation without going through the overhead of first creating a date object.

Returns:
The millisecond representation of the current date instance, that is, the number of milliseconds between midnight (GMT) on 1/1/1970 and the date and time specified by the date.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
setTime(Object), JsGlobal.Date.parse(Object), JsGlobal.Date.UTC(Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.UTC(Object, Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.UTC(Object, Object, Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.UTC(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.UTC(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object, Object), JsGlobal.Date.UTC(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object, Object, Object), DateLikes.getTime(DateLike)
JavaScript:

getTimezoneOffset

java.lang.Number getTimezoneOffset()

Returns the difference, in minutes, between the local and UTC representations of the current date instance. Note that the value returned depends on whether daylight saving time is or would be in effect at the specific date.

The return value is measured in minutes, rather than hours, because some countries have time zones that are not at even one-hour intervals.

Returns:
The difference, in minutes, between GMT and local time.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
DateLikes.getTimezoneOffset(DateLike)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current date instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

setTime

java.lang.Number setTime(java.lang.Object time)

Sets the fields of the current date instance using the millisecond format.

Parameters:
time - The number of milliseconds between the desired date and time and midnight GMT on January 1, 1970. A millisecond value of this type may also be passed to the Js.date(Number), JsDate.JsDate(Number), JsDate.JsDate(NumberLike), JsDate.JsDate(String), JsDate.JsDate(StringLike), JsGlobal.Date.create(Number) or JsGlobal.Date.create(Number) and may be obtained by calling the JsGlobal.Date.UTC(Object, Object) and JsGlobal.Date.parse(Object) methods. Representing a date in this millisecond format makes it independent of time zone.
Returns:
The time argument. Prior to ECMAScript standardization, this method returns nothing.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
DateLikes.setTime(DateLike, Object)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current date instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

toLocaleString

java.lang.String toLocaleString()

Converts a date to a string, using the local time zone and the local date formatting conventions.

This method also uses local conventions for date and time formatting, so the format may vary from platform to platform and from country to country. It returns a string formatted in what is likely the user's preferred date and time format.

Returns:
A string representation of the date and time specified by the current date instance. The date and time are represented in the local time zone and formatted using locally appropriate conventions.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
toLocaleDateString(), toLocaleTimeString(), toString(), toUTCString(), DateLikes.toLocaleString(DateLike)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the interface invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current date instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

var

JsDate var()

Simply returns the date object of the current date instance.

This method is useful for JS Simulation to implement opaque types.

If the current instance is a Java simulated date and the method runs in JS Embed Simulation mode, the invocation creates and returns a JavaScript Date object as a runtime copy of the current instance.

Returns:
The date object of the current instance.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must ignore the interface invocation of this method, that is, replacing it with its current instance.
